  "body": "Our `kubectl get rc` output is extremely wide:\n\n```\n$ kubectl get rc\nCONTROLLER                CONTAINER(S)                           IMAGE(S)                                                                                               SELECTOR                                                                                                                   REPLICAS   AGE\nconvert-mon-rc-dev        convert-mon                            docker-registry.dev.internal.box/sam/convert-mon:0.0.0-21.2015_12_31_22_37_37.56e95-image-16           box.com/app-id=convert-mon,box.com/env=dev,box.com/version=2015-12-13                                                      1          16d\nconvert-mon-rc-live       convert-mon                            docker-registry.dev.internal.box/sam/convert-mon:0.0.0-21.2015_12_31_22_37_37.56e95-image-16           box.com/app-id=convert-mon,box.com/env=live,box.com/version=2015-12-13                                                     1          16d\nconvert-mon-rc-sanity     convert-mon                            docker-registry.dev.internal.box/sam/convert-mon:0.0.0-21.2015_12_31_22_37_37.56e95-image-16           box.com/app-id=convert-mon,box.com/env=sanity,box.com/version=2015-12-13                                                   1          16d\n...\n```\n\n(Note the columns are wider than the text because I've omitted rows that have longer text in them.)\n\nI would contend that when you are typically trying to list RC's, you're mostly looking for (1) which ones exist, (2) how many replicas they have and perhaps (3) the selector. Usually the name is enough to remind you what's inside of it, but if you want all the details of what specific containers and images it has you can do `kubectl describe rc <x>` or `kubectl describe pod <x>`. As such I suggest moving CONTAINER(S) and IMAGE(S) columns into -o wide only.\n",
